Checkpointing, and fault tolerance.

Checkpointing is the mechanism that makes structured streaming exactly-once, and restartable. Without it, a crashed query restarts from scratch, and it may double-process the data.

Now, a checkpoint is not just the last offset read. It is three things — and they all advance atomically, every batch.

The first is the offsets — the source positions, like a file index or a Kafka offset. This is what has been read.

The second is the write-ahead log — what has been planned for this batch. This is what recovers the in-flight data if the driver crashes.

And the third is the state store snapshot — the running aggregates, the window contents, and the join buffers.

All three of these move forward in one atomic commit, per batch. And that atomicity is exactly how Spark gives you exactly-once — there is never a window where the offsets advance but the state does not, or the reverse.

So always set checkpoint-location on any production query. But remember — end-to-end exactly-once requires both the source and the sink to support it. Kafka into Delta is exactly-once. Rate into memory is only at-least-once, because the sink is not durable. And a socket source into anything is at-most-once, because the source is not replayable.
